Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, City of Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whipple","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: perhaps a nickname from an unrecorded diminutive of Middle English <i>w(h)ippe</i> ‘scourge, whip’, possibly contained in Middle English <i>whippel-tre</i>, a type of dogwood or <i>cornus</i>. For possible applications as a nickname see   Whipp  . Alternatively, perhaps from an unrecorded diminutive of the Middle English personal name <i>Wippe</i> (see   Whipp  ).","History: Matthew Whipple came from England to Ipswich, MA, <i>c.</i> 1638. His descendent William Whipple (1730–85) born in Kittery, ME, was a signer of the Declaration of Independence. A John Whipple was one of the first settlers in Providence, RI."],"variants":[{"name":"Whipp","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Wippe</i> (Old English <i>Wippa</i>, of unexplained etymology but apparently attested in the Isle of Wight placename Whippingham and in an Anglo-Saxon field name <i>Wippan hoh</i> ‘Wippa's hill-spur’). Alternatively, perhaps from Middle English <i>whip(pe)</i>, <i>wipp(e)</i> ‘whip’, either as an occupational name for someone who used a whip, as corporal punishment or to drive or control animals, or a nickname for a lively, quick-moving person, or someone generally in a hurry."]},{"name":"Whippo","meanings":["English: variant of   Whipple  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas II Whipple was born in 1450, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Thomas I Whipple. He had at least 1 son with Lady Isabelle Stewart Duchess of Brittany. He died on 20 February 1557, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 107, and was buried in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1450–20 February 1557":"1450–20. veebruar 1557","1450–1557":"1450–1557","1445–1556":"1445–1556","1489–1557":"1489–1557","1475–1557":"1475–1557","1521–1582":"1521–1582","1430–1457":"1430–1457","1450":"1450","1582":"1582","1557":"1557","1457":"1457","1556":"1556","1489":"1489","1445":"1445","1521":"1521","1475":"1475","1430":"1430","20 February 1556":"20. veebruar 1556","20 February 1557":"20. veebruar 1557","February 1557":"veebruar 1557","20 Feb 1557":"20. veebruar 1557","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, City of Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1450–20 February 1557":"1450–20. helmikuuta 1557","1450–1557":"1450–1557","1445–1556":"1445–1556","1489–1557":"1489–1557","1475–1557":"1475–1557","1521–1582":"1521–1582","1430–1457":"1430–1457","1450":"1450","1582":"1582","1557":"1557","1457":"1457","1556":"1556","1489":"1489","1445":"1445